1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,080
 Hey, this is Brian from Fullstack Egg.

2
00:00:03,080 --> 00:00:04,920
 When we set up paperless,

3
00:00:04,920 --> 00:00:07,560
 we use something called Docker,

4
00:00:07,560 --> 00:00:10,360
 and I'm going to tell you a little bit about it.

5
00:00:10,360 --> 00:00:16,520
 You can think of Docker like a collection of shipping containers that all have different things inside,

6
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:21,040
 but because they are all inside of that same container,

7
00:00:21,040 --> 00:00:23,640
 it makes it really easy to manage,

8
00:00:23,640 --> 00:00:27,080
 and Docker does the same thing for software.

9
00:00:27,080 --> 00:00:31,480
 Instead of installing a program and hoping it works on your computer,

10
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:35,240
 everything the program needs gets packed into a container.

11
00:00:35,240 --> 00:00:38,640
 So when you run that container, it just works,

12
00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:42,520
 and it doesn't matter if you're running it on your desktop computer

13
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:46,800
 or on a VPS in the cloud, it always works the same.

14
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:50,640
 So this is Docker desktop on my Mac,

15
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:55,000
 and these are the containers running paperless right now on my computer.

16
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,440
 There's a few of them working together, one for the database,

17
00:00:58,440 --> 00:01:00,320
 one for paperless itself,

18
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:03,480
 and one for the search add-on that we built.

19
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:07,600
 And here I'll show you them running in the terminal as well.

20
00:01:07,600 --> 00:01:10,000
 Each one is running in its own little box,

21
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,320
 keeping things clean and separate.

22
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:15,040
 And while this all might seem complicated,

23
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:18,080
 you really don't have to be a programmer to set this up.

24
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:21,000
 Docker handles all the complicated parts.

25
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:23,080
 You basically say, "Run this,"

26
00:01:23,080 --> 00:01:26,160
 and it pulls everything down and starts it up.

27
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:30,440
 And if something breaks, you throw away the container and start fresh.

28
00:01:30,440 --> 00:01:34,400
 Your data is stored separately, so nothing gets lost.

29
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:36,760
 So that's Docker in a nutshell.

30
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:40,240
 It packages software, so it runs the same everywhere,

31
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:43,400
 and you don't have to worry about installing all these dependencies

32
00:01:43,400 --> 00:01:45,400
 and breaking things.

33
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:48,760
 And for the paperless install videos,

34
00:01:48,760 --> 00:01:52,760
 you'll see that our setup script handles all the Docker stuff for you,

35
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:56,720
 automatically, so you really don't have to worry about it.

36
00:01:56,720 --> 00:01:58,160
 And that's it for now.

37
00:01:58,160 --> 00:01:59,880
 Thanks again for watching.

